Context and Objectives
• Here are some bullets, implemented as unicode because there
are prettier.
• On inkscape OSX, avoid copy-paste in favor of duplicate (Ctrl-D)
• Boxes are grouped, which includes:
• a white box
• a top blue box with white text
• Avoid changing size of the whole group of box, instead, degroup
the box, change the size of the white box, and move the title box
• Snap to grid for a better layout
You don't have to use bullets for everything.
Note that:
• The Inserm logo has been changed to white, according to
Inserm's chart of usage. TL;DR: use white when background is
dark.

Method
Put a cool phrase in bold, everyone likes bolds.
There are different kind of bolds.
• If inkscape becomes slow (this is an A0 image!), you may want to switch to outline mode in View->Display Mode->Outline mode,
which is much much faster for prototyping
• Want LaTeX ? Three choices:
• Extensions -> Render -> Formula. If you do not have LaTeX and pstoedit installed, this option will not appear in Inkscape
• Tex Text extension. It might be difficult to install because of the python path mess of OSX. Thank you Steve Jobs!
• Use LaTeXit, an app included in mactex, save the formula in PDF and the import the PDF in File->Import
• Want figures ? I guess you want the figures of your paper. I guess that you saved them in PDF. No? What? PNG? That's gonna look
horrible in an A0 paper. Remember that this poster is huge.
Get a scalable format first (pdf, svg) and then import with File->Import. You can import your whole paper and
then select and erase all the text.
Here's an arrow, it might prove useful.
I did it with a rectangle, a triangle (3 points polygon) and a path union
You can do more complicated shapes, of course.
